<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920214-0048</DOCNO><DOCID>920214-0048.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>02/14/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   SALES OF U.S.-MADE CARS rose sharply in early Februaryfrom the dismal levels of the preceding weeks, feeding hopesthat the auto industry's recession is easing. Light-trucksales surged, as they often do at the beginning of arecovery.                                                                                                       </LP><TEXT>   Retail sales climbed 0.6% in January, and sales data forDecember and November were revised upward. But analysts saidit is too soon to declare a true recovery in consumer demand.Separately, unemployment claims fell in the latest weeklyperiod.   ---   Bond and stock prices tumbled and the dollar soaredagainst the mark as a poorly received Treasury auction andstrong retail sales com bined to paint a picture of risinginterest rates. Treasury bonds plunged about 1 1/8 points.The Dow Jones in dustrials sank 30.18 points to 3246.65.   ---   Ford's fourth-quarter loss narrowed to $475.6 million butstill resulted in a record $2.26 billion loss for the year.The car maker predicted improved operating results in 1992.                                                                                                          General Motors and Ford are cutting or eliminating rebateson several models after more than a year of sweetening suchsales incentives.   ---   A top Democrat proposed lowering income taxes forcorporations and middle-income people and cutting the capitalgains tax for some investors. Higher taxes on upper-incomepeople would pay for the $90.9 billion cost.   ---   OPEC members remained split over how much to reduce theiroil output and how to share the cuts.   ---   Tokyo's four big brokerage firms proposed loosening rulesthat limit their trading, in an effort to revitalize Japan'sstock market, where prices are down 43% from the end of 1989.   ---   Japan's trade surplus quadrupled in January from a yearearlier as exports climbed 9.7%. Imports fell 3.8%, largelydue to lower oil prices. The surplus with the U.S. rose 2.4%.                                                                                                          Daihatsu Motor is withdrawing from the U.S. market,marking the first time a Japanese auto maker did so in morethan three decades.   ---   Colgate-Palmolive agreed to acquire Mennen, a toiletriesconcern with the No. 1 deodorant brand, for $670 million,mostly in stock.   ---   Insurers may limit new coverage of health problems linkedto breast implants if the FDA bans the devices. The companieswould treat the implants as &quot;pre-existing conditions.&quot;   ---   Unisys is close to an agreement with its bank lenders thatwould take considerable pressure off the heavily indebtedcomputer maker, according to people familiar with the talks.   ---   Mirage Resorts is joining with two Indian tribes to buildand run casinos in Kansas and Washington state.   ---   Jack Eckerd Corp. withdrew its bid for Revco, making itlikely Revco management's plan to emerge from Chapter 11 willbe adopted.   ---   Russia set up a committee to reexamine the awarding of acontract to explore oil and gas development off Sakhalinisland to a consortium of Mitsui, Marathon and McDermott.   ---   Manufacturers remain optimistic about the short-termeconomic outlook, according to a survey.   ---   American Express pulled a commercial after just one airingbecause it resembled a Long Island bank's ad.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 229,360,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials3246.65, off 30.18; transportation 1386.21, off 19.43;utilities 208.12, off 1.82.   Bonds: Lehman Brothers Treasury index 4163.99, off 45.96.   Commodities: Oil $19.68 a barrel, up 41 cents. Dow Jonesfutures index 121.84, off 0.64; spot index 119.05, off 0.29.   Dollar: 127.65 yen, up 0.20; 1.6241 marks, up 0.0167.</TEXT></DOC>